<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-12-20T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-12-20T16:00:00-05:00" n="117" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d117">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">710.G Women’s Rights/17:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Chairman of the American
                                    Delegation</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Hull</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-12-20T16:00:00-05:00">December 20, 1933—4
                                        p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>106. My 105, December 20, 3 p.m. For your information the National
                                Woman’s Party has just received a telegram from Miss Doris Stevens
                                announcing that the United States will sign the Treaty on
                                Nationality. Neither the White House nor the State Department is
                                making any official statement in this regard awaiting your
                                action.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>